<Author>GreyFlame
<Content>A small-roomed, smelly last resort First of all, if you visit this hotel's website and look around you'll find pictures of the lobby and one of the rooms. I'd say that the lobby picture isn't that deceiving, if you can accept that what you see in the picture is all there is to the place, save for a tiny niche containing a circle of couches and a table. There is a toilet, but this is actually a shared toilet with the adjoining restaurant, and requires a walk through an incredibly shoddy and depressing hallway.The elevators up the hotel are inconveniently shaped and are cramped like none I have been in before and there are no staff to help you bring your luggage up (although in my experience there were almost no staff to help you do anything). The lift stopped at the 16th floor and when the doors opened my first thought was Basil Fawlty, the hallway was stark white with imitation foam as a ceiling, some of which was sagging for God's sake.Since I was travelling with a small group at peak season, we split in to pairs and had adjacent rooms at the rear corners of the hotel. Me and my partner opened the door with a sense of foreboding, and when it swung open I felt like I was going to laugh at how ridiculously bad the room was and break down crying about the fact I was staying in it.I walked over to my friends' room and it appeared to be even worse, there was a rough hole in the bedside table and the ceiling was cracked concrete. I walked to the curtains and threw them open to be met by two large panes of immovable, frosted glass. My disappointment increased when I ran back to my room to inspect the area behind the curtains to find one frosted pane, and one normal one giving my a stunning city-scape view: towers of dejectedly browning slum-like buildings.The rooms were ludicrously small (I'd guess 2.5m by 3m), barely fitting two beds, a desk, a poorly positioned closet, a mirror, a TV, a fluorescent light and two wall-mounted lamps. Those lights and lamps were the one of two sources of light and they failed at being those very things. That was accompanied by the fact that the only other source was sunlight from the windows, and that light requires you to view that horrid sight of deteriorating buildings. The beds were insanely uncomfortable, causing me to change positions every few minutes (even when I was sitting on it) and making me have a back ache in the morning.The room constantly stank of a dank stench similar to that of a basement, only the room also had carpet to absorb it. We bought a can of disinfectant spray to combat it, but it took three rounds of spraying to make it bearable. The TV had an average-to-poor amount of reception, and very limited channels, although it was edging on alright.The bathroom is a roughly 1.5m by 2.5m area with a small bath, a toilet and a basin with nothing to hide the grimy pipes below it. To be fair it stank a lot less than the actual room and I could bear to be in it for a fair length of time. That's it on the rooms, you can make the judgement on whether you like them or not, but I for one severely disliked them.I had a few normal run-ins with the staff, two with the reception (which was okay) and two with doormen/informative standing people. The first was alright, and he helped us make it to the ferry and to Hong Kong island, and the second helped us call a taxi to another ferry terminal that we would take to leave to another destination. The latter sped off with our luggage, forcing one of us to run to keep him in sight just in case he ran off for good, and he managed to get four of us and oh so many pieces of luggage jammed into the car. Although he could've done worse, this was less than desirable.The location of the hotel just gives you access to shops plastered with flashy neon signs, most saying 'Sony', and many people trying to force you into their shops to buy something, though the only reason you would would be so you could just go away and be left alone. The hotel gets points for being near the MTR station but when it comes to location that's all I can give it that's positive.All in all, stay away from the Imperial Hotel in Hong Kong unless it's the absolute last option you have to be able to stay in Hong Kong territory, and even then, you may consider just not going in order to avoid this atrocity, because if you befall the same fate I did, your opinion of Hong Kong will become very low, and the best time you'll have with the hotel is the time you check out. 
